  <refnamediv>
	<refname>lod_create</refname>
	<refpurpose>Create a new liblod context</refpurpose>
  </refnamediv>
  
  <refsynopsisdiv>
	<funcsynopsis>
	  <funcsynopsisinfo>#include &lt;liblod.h&gt;</funcsynopsisinfo>
	  <funcprototype>
		<funcdef>LODCONTEXT *<function>lod_create</function></funcdef>
		<void />
	  </funcprototype>
	</funcsynopsis>
  </refsynopsisdiv>

  <refsect1>
	<title>Description</title>
	
	<para>
	  <function>lod_create</function> allocates a new <package>liblod</package>
	  context. Typically, a context is created for a single discovery
	  session, with its own <type>librdf_model</type> and
	  <package>libcurl</package> handle. One or more URIs can be resolved
	  (retrieving the data related to them from Linked Open Data web servers
	  and populating the model), the model interrogated, and the context
	  eventually destroyed to free the resources associated with it.
	</para>
  </refsect1>

  <refsect1>
	<title>Notes</title>
	<para>
	  If your application needs to call <function>curl_global_init</function>
	  with any value other than <constant>CURL_GLOBAL_ALL</constant>, you
	  should invoke it prior to calling <function>lod_create</function> for
	  the first time.
	</para>
  </refsect1>

